The paper deals with graph partitioning problems, which are typically studied in the computer science subfield of discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The use of spectral methods for partitioning is a common technique in machine learning and data analysis, which falls under the subfield of computational statistics (cs.SI). The paper also involves analytical computations of the spectral density, which is a numerical analysis technique that falls under the subfield of numerical analysis (cs.NA). The study of graph ensembles and their properties is a topic in graph theory (cs.GT), and the paper proposes a conjecture on the absence of an efficient recovery detectability transition, which is a topic in statistical learning theory (cs.LG).
